# UXIP‑1: Authoring Guidelines for UXIPs

Version: 0.1  
Status: Draft  
Category: Process  
Author: Alluwamna  
Created: 2026‑03‑22  

---

## Abstract

This document defines the minimal authoring requirements for UX Improvement
Proposals (UXIPs). UXIP‑1 specifies the mandatory sections that every UXIP must
include, along with optional sections authors may use when appropriate. The goal
is to ensure clarity and consistency while keeping UXIPs lightweight and easy to
produce.

---

## 1. Introduction

UXIP‑0 defines the lifecycle and governance process for UXIPs. UXIP‑1
complements that document by defining the minimal structure required for
authoring UXIPs.

Only the sections strictly necessary for understanding, evaluating, and
maintaining a UXIP are mandatory. All other sections are optional.

---

## 2. Mandatory Sections

Every UXIP must include the following sections, in the order listed below.

### (1) Header

The header must include:

- UXIP number  
- Title  
- Version  
- Status  
- Category  
- Author(s)  
- Created date  

### (2) Abstract

A short summary of the proposal. The abstract should be concise and limited to
high‑level context.

### (3) Introduction

Context and motivation for the proposal. This section explains the background
and why the UXIP exists.

### (4) Proposal

The main content of the UXIP. This section describes the change, idea, or
process being proposed. Authors may structure this section as needed, including
subsections such as “Specification,” “Process Overview,” or “Lifecycle.”

### (5) Rationale

A brief explanation of why the proposed approach was chosen over alternatives.

### (6) Copyright

All UXIPs must include the statement:  
“This document is in the public domain.”

---

## 3. Optional Sections

Authors may include any of the following sections when relevant. These sections
are not required.

### (1) Reference Implementation

Example code, pseudocode, or implementation notes.

### (2) Economic Considerations

Analysis of incentives, costs, or market effects.

### (3) Governance Considerations

Notes on how the proposal interacts with governance processes.

### (4) Appendix

Supplemental material that supports the proposal but is not essential to the
main text.

---

## 4. Formatting Guidance

These guidelines are recommended but not mandatory.

- Use plain text or simple Markdown.  
- Keep language clear and concise.  
- Avoid unnecessary formatting.  
- Maintain consistent structure across UXIPs.  

---

## 5. Relationship to UXIP‑0

UXIP‑0 defines how UXIPs progress through Draft, Review, and Final stages.
UXIP‑1 defines the minimal structure required for authoring UXIPs.

Together, these documents ensure that UXIPs are both procedurally sound and
consistently written.

---

## 6. Rationale

A minimal set of mandatory sections keeps UXIPs easy to write while ensuring
that proposals remain clear, comparable, and maintainable. Optional sections
allow authors to include additional detail when appropriate without imposing
unnecessary requirements.

---

